A lot of the best advice boils down to this: treat AI like a fast junior-to-mid collaborator with weird strengths, not like an oracle. The experienced developers who seem to benefit most are the ones who keep their engineering standards high and move the AI into the parts of the loop where speed matters most. GitHub explicitly argues that AI makes expertise more important, because speed only helps if someone is still making the architectural, security, and maintainability judgments.  ￼

A practical shift that tends to work well is to become much more spec-first. Write tighter tasks, sharper acceptance criteria, and clearer interfaces than you used to. Cursor’s agent guide says agents do best when goals are verifiable and correctness is signaled with typed languages, linters, and tests; GitHub is also pushing spec-driven development as a good match for AI workflows.  ￼ That matches what you’ve already noticed with Jira-ticket-like prompts and defined APIs.

The other big adjustment is to separate planning from execution. Ask the model for a plan, then have it implement one bounded step at a time, then review the diff. Cursor recommends starting with plans, managing context carefully, and reviewing changes rather than letting the agent disappear into vague autonomy. Anthropic’s guidance on agents makes a similar point: simple, composable patterns tend to work better than overcomplicated frameworks.  ￼

For someone with 10+ years of experience, the sweet spot is usually to use AI most aggressively for drafting, search, rote refactors, test scaffolding, glue code, migration chores, and "show me the likely shape" tasks, while keeping humans firmly in charge of architecture, invariants, naming, interfaces, and production risk. GitHub and Anthropic both emphasize that developers are shifting toward higher-level work managing AI systems rather than handing over judgment wholesale.  ￼

It also helps to optimize your repo for agents. That means strong types, fast tests, linters, deterministic build steps, and explicit repo instructions. Cursor says typed languages, linters, and tests give agents clear success signals, and GitHub has written specifically about agents.md files as a way to encode repo-specific expectations and reduce wandering behavior. GitHub also notes that typed languages are gaining ground in AI-assisted workflows in part because they are easier for both humans and models to reason about safely.  ￼

One more pattern: restart early when the context degrades. Long agent runs can drift, loop, or become overconfident. Anthropic’s long-running agent guidance discusses context management and compaction as real concerns, not edge cases. In practice, experienced devs often get better results by killing a fuzzy run, restating the task more sharply, and resuming from a clean checkpoint than by trying to salvage a confused agent thread.  ￼

So the short version is: keep standards high, make tasks smaller and more testable, use AI where iteration speed dominates, and treat clarity of interface as a force multiplier. If you want, I can turn that into a compact "AI-assisted dev operating rules for senior engineers" note in your Beast style.







