A linter is a program that reads your code and complains before the compiler or runtime has to.

At the simplest level:

compiler: this is invalid
linter: this is valid but suspicious / inconsistent / ugly / risky

For someone with your background, the most useful way to think about linters is:

lint = automated code review for repeatable low-level annoyances

They catch things humans are bad at catching consistently, especially when tired.

what linters do

They usually enforce some mix of:
	•	style
	•	correctness hints
	•	unsafe patterns
	•	maintainability rules

Examples:
	•	unused variable
	•	shadowed variable
	•	missing error check
	•	inconsistent naming
	•	unreachable code
	•	suspicious comparison
	•	formatting drift

A linter will not prove your allocator is correct. But it will catch a lot of friction and some real bugs.

why they matter more with AI-assisted coding

AI generates a lot of code that is:

plausible
consistent-looking
slightly wrong

A linter gives you an immediate low-cost filter.

So the loop becomes:

prompt
→ generate code
→ run linter
→ fix obvious issues
→ run tests
→ then review deeper logic

That is much better than reading raw AI output cold.

the three neighboring tools

People often blur these together:

1. linter

Checks code for suspicious patterns and rule violations.

2. formatter

Rewrites code layout automatically.

Example:
	•	indentation
	•	line wrapping
	•	spacing

3. type checker / compiler

Checks syntax and type correctness.

In practice many ecosystems use all three together.

concrete examples

C / C++

You’ll often see:
	•	clang-tidy = linter / static analysis
	•	clang-format = formatter
	•	compiler warnings like -Wall -Wextra -Werror

For C, compiler warnings are already a huge part of the lint story.

Python
	•	ruff = very fast linter, increasingly standard
	•	black = formatter
	•	mypy = optional type checker

JavaScript / TypeScript
	•	eslint = linter
	•	prettier = formatter
	•	tsc = type checker for TypeScript

what a linter feels like

Suppose you write:

int x;
if (condition) {
    int x = 5;
    return x;
}
return x;

A linter may warn:
	•	outer x might be uninitialized
	•	inner x shadows outer x

The code may compile, but the linter is telling you:

this is legal
but smells wrong

That is its job.

how to start without drowning

Do not start with 500 rules.

Start with:

1. compiler warnings high
2. formatter on
3. one linter with a small ruleset

For your C work, a very sane first setup is:
	•	compiler warnings:
	•	-Wall
	•	-Wextra
	•	maybe -Wpedantic
	•	formatter:
	•	clang-format
	•	linter / static analysis:
	•	clang-tidy

That alone gets you a lot.

mental model for rules

Lint rules usually fall into these buckets:

style

Example:
	•	naming
	•	brace position
	•	line length

Useful, but lower value.

bug-risk

Example:
	•	uninitialized values
	•	shadowing
	•	ignored return values

High value.

maintainability

Example:
	•	giant functions
	•	duplicate branches
	•	confusing expressions

Often valuable.

overreach / busywork

Example:
	•	extremely picky rules that slow you down

These should often be disabled.

