Your instincts are coherent, but they pull in two different directions:
	•	large, explicit, inspectable units
	•	responsive background execution

You can absolutely have both, but you should separate API shape, file layout, and runtime architecture.

1. one function per file, large functions

That can work if the function is a true operation boundary, not just a random pile of logic.

Your examples:

beastDrawGallery(...)
beastQueueImageGen(...)

make sense as top-level operations.

The danger is not "large function" by itself. The danger is:

one large function with no internal structure

A good compromise is:
	•	one primary exported function per file
	•	private helper functions in same file if needed
	•	file name matches operation

Example:

beast_draw_gallery.c
  beastDrawGallery(...)
  static beastDrawGalleryVisibleRange(...)
  static beastDrawGalleryTile(...)
  static beastDrawGalleryOverlay(...)

So the file still has one public purpose, but you do not force all logic into one giant body.

That usually beats literal one-function-per-file.

2. verbose headers, explicit mutable scope

Yes, this is a very systems-friendly style.

Something like:

void beastDrawGallery(
    BeastGalleryItemsRingBuffer *galleryItemsRingBuffer,
    const BeastGalleryDimensions *galleryDimensions,
    BeastDrawBuffer *drawBuffer);

is much better than hiding mutation behind globals.

I would strongly recommend these rules:
	•	all mutable state passed explicitly
	•	read-only inputs marked const
	•	output buffers explicit
	•	ownership obvious
	•	pointer means nullable only if truly nullable

So instead of "pointer or reference" in C terms:
	•	pointer for mutable or optional
	•	const * for read-only large input
	•	plain value for small immutable scalars

Example:

void beastQueueImageGen(
    BeastImageGenQueue *queue,
    const char *positivePrompt,
    const char *modelName,
    const BeastImageGenOptions *options,
    BeastJobId *outJobId);

That is explicit and reviewable.

3. exhaustive mutable scope list

This is often a good idea, but avoid passing the universe.

Bad:

beastDrawGallery(appState, uiState, renderState, jobsState, dbState, ...)

Better:

beastDrawGallery(galleryView, galleryLayout, drawBuffer)

If a function needs too many pieces, that is often a signal to create a narrow operation struct:

typedef struct BeastDrawGalleryContext {
    BeastGalleryItemsRingBuffer *galleryItemsRingBuffer;
    const BeastGalleryDimensions *galleryDimensions;
    BeastDrawBuffer *drawBuffer;
} BeastDrawGalleryContext;

Then:

void beastDrawGallery(BeastDrawGalleryContext *ctx);

This preserves explicitness without absurd parameter lists.

4. does C have a central dispatcher for background tasks like Objective-C?

Not built in the same way.

C gives you primitives, not a rich runtime model.

Depending on platform, you typically use:
	•	POSIX threads on Unix-like systems
	•	Win32 threads on Windows
	•	a custom job queue / thread pool
	•	a library like SDL threads, libuv, etc.

So the answer is:

C has no universal built-in "dispatcher"
you usually build one or adopt one

For Beast, that is probably fine. You likely want your own job system anyway.

5. best background threading architecture

For Beast, I would not start with "many arbitrary threads."

I would start with:

main thread

Owns:
	•	UI
	•	input
	•	presentation
	•	command dispatch

background worker thread pool

Owns:
	•	image generation requests
	•	DB operations that may block
	•	file loading / thumbnails
	•	expensive preprocessing

optional dedicated GPU / model execution coordinator

Owns:
	•	serialized access to model pipelines
	•	queue ordering
	•	cancellation / status

That is usually the sweet spot.

simple shape

main thread
→ push job into queue
→ worker picks up job
→ worker posts result/event back
→ main thread integrates result

This is much saner than letting background threads mutate UI state directly.

6. two processes better?

Sometimes yes.

threads are better when:
	•	shared memory is helpful
	•	low latency matters
	•	you trust the code
	•	you want simpler data sharing

separate processes are better when:
	•	crashes must be isolated
	•	model runtimes are unstable
	•	GPU / Python / third-party libs are messy
	•	you want restartability

For Beast image generation specifically, separate process can be very attractive.

Example:

beast_ui process
beast_worker process

UI stays alive even if worker crashes.

That is a big deal.

My recommendation:

for v0.3

Use:
	•	one process
	•	main thread + worker threads
if you need speed and simplicity

for Beast 1.0

Strongly consider:
	•	UI process
	•	worker process
especially if model execution is heavy or unstable

7. central dispatcher design in Beast terms

You probably want a job dispatcher, not a generic thread abstraction.

Something like:

typedef enum BeastJobType {
    BEAST_JOB_IMAGE_GEN,
    BEAST_JOB_LOAD_THUMBNAIL,
    BEAST_JOB_DB_WRITE,
    BEAST_JOB_IMPORT_ARTIFACT
} BeastJobType;

Then:

bool beastSubmitJob(BeastJobQueue *queue, const BeastJob *job);
bool beastPollJobResult(BeastJobResultQueue *queue, BeastJobResult *outResult);

That gives you:
	•	inspectability
	•	logging
	•	cancellation
	•	replayability

This matches Beast much better than "fire off threads."

8. best threading rule for Beast UI

Very strong rule:

background threads do work
main thread owns truth for ui state

Workers may produce results.
Main thread commits them.

That avoids a lot of pain.

9. where C++ has a performance advantage over C

Usually, not much by default. C++ is not magically faster.

Often performance is equal if codegen is similar.

But C++ can have practical advantages that lead to better performance or lower overhead designs.

places C++ can help

templates / generic zero-cost abstractions
You mentioned:

byte-equivalent struct reuse queues but different type

Yes, this is a real advantage.

In C++:

template<typename T>
class RingBuffer { ... };

You get:
	•	type-safe reuse
	•	no void-pointer casts
	•	often zero runtime overhead

In C, you fake this with:
	•	macros
	•	void pointers
	•	code generation
	•	duplicated implementations

C++ is better here.

RAII
Not raw speed, but fewer leaks / cleaner lifetime management can improve real-world performance and stability.

move semantics
Can reduce copies in some designs.

inline generic algorithms
You can write reusable containers and helpers without paying abstraction tax.

where C is still great
	•	predictable ABI
	•	simple compilation model
	•	easier inspection
	•	less language surface area
	•	fewer hidden behaviors

For Beast, if your core value is:

clarity
inspectability
simple mental model

then C is still a very strong fit.

If you start wanting:
	•	reusable typed containers
	•	generic queues
	•	cleaner ownership wrappers
	•	stronger compile-time abstractions

then carefully constrained C++ may become attractive.

10. pragmatic recommendation

For Beast desktop now:

code style
	•	one public operation per file
	•	helpers allowed in same file
	•	explicit mutable state
	•	const aggressively used
	•	narrow operation context structs when argument lists get absurd

threading
	•	main thread for UI
	•	worker queue for background jobs
	•	no direct worker mutation of UI state

process model
	•	start single-process
	•	move model execution to separate worker process if instability appears

language
	•	C first is fine
	•	revisit C++ only if generic containers / typed queues / ownership patterns become painful enough to justify it

