i thought i heard at a conference that the latest version of c has passable code blocks ideal for generic dispatcher?













You’re remembering something real adjacent, but not quite that.

Short answer:

no -- C does not (yet) have true closures / code blocks suitable for a generic dispatcher

But there are three nearby things people often confuse:

⸻

1. Apple "blocks" (what you likely heard)

On macOS / iOS, there is a C extension called Blocks.

Syntax:

void (^myBlock)(int) = ^(int x) {
    printf("%d\n", x);
};

These are:
	•	function-like objects
	•	can capture variables (like closures)
	•	integrate with Grand Central Dispatch

Example:

dispatch_async(queue, ^{
    printf("hello from worker\n");
});


⸻

why they feel perfect for a dispatcher

Because you can write:

dispatch_async(queue, ^{
    doWork(x, y, z);
});

No need for:
	•	job structs
	•	enum types
	•	unions

Very clean.

⸻

why Beast probably should NOT rely on them

They are:
	•	non-standard C
	•	Apple/Clang-specific
	•	not portable to:
	•	Windows
	•	Linux
	•	Android (reliably)

So:

great locally on mac
bad for cross-platform core


⸻

2. C23 (latest C standard)

C23 added improvements, but not closures / blocks.

Relevant additions:
	•	better attributes
	•	improved type features
	•	minor ergonomics

But no:

no lambda
no closure
no capturing code block

So:

your generic dispatcher cannot rely on standard C closures


⸻

3. classic C workaround (what Beast should use)

C-style dispatcher uses:

function pointer + void *context

Example:

typedef void (*BeastJobFn)(void *ctx);

typedef struct BeastJob {
    BeastJobFn fn;
    void *ctx;
