sokol vs sdl






For Beast, the split is pretty clean:

SDL is the safer choice if you want a broad, batteries-included foundation.
sokol is the cleaner choice if you want a thin substrate and plan to build most of the UI yourself.

A few current facts help frame it. SDL has stable SDL3 releases, with 3.4.4 listed on the official releases page, and SDL positions itself around windows, input, audio, and rendering.  ￼ Sokol, by contrast, describes itself as a collection of minimal standalone cross-platform C headers, with WebAssembly as a first-class target, and its core modules are intentionally independent from each other.  ￼

For your Beast rewrite, SDL wins on practicality if your priority is "get the shell alive fast." It gives you more of the boring platform work out of the box: windowing, input, audio, and a mature ecosystem of examples around real apps and games. SDL3 also now has an official examples directory and endorsed examples, which matters when you’re trying to anchor AI-assisted implementation to known patterns instead of hand-wavy guesses.  ￼

sokol wins on architectural cleanliness if your priority is "thin, explicit, custom workstation UI." It is much smaller in concept, easier to mentally hold, and fits your preference for explicit state and custom-drawn interfaces. It also has a stronger "minimal substrate" vibe for something Beast-like, where you want your own gallery, command bar, artifact panels, and vectoring UI rather than inherited widget behavior. Sokol’s docs and samples emphasize that minimal, standalone design.  ￼

For text and fonts, neither library magically removes the hard part. SDL gives you a more comfortable platform layer overall, but good text still usually pushes you toward a real font stack. With sokol, you are even more explicitly assembling the stack yourself. So if text editing, prompt entry, selection, and crisp font rendering are near-term blockers, SDL gives you a less lonely road. If your first goal is more like "draw panels, images, overlays, command line, and a few text labels," sokol is perfectly viable.

For threading and job dispatch, neither choice solves your Beast dispatcher design for you. Your earlier decision stands: main thread owns visible UI truth, workers do background jobs, results come back for integration. SDL does not replace that architecture, and sokol certainly does not either. That means the real question is less "which one has the better threading model" and more "which one gives me the right amount of platform help while staying out of the way."

My blunt recommendation for Beast 0.3:
	•	Choose SDL if you want the fastest path to a working desktop shell with fewer platform surprises.
	•	Choose sokol if you are ready to fully commit to a custom-drawn Beast UI and want the thinnest possible base.

Given what you said--UI/UX is the main blocker, you want to do it right, and you are rewriting anyway--I’d lean SDL for early momentum and sokol only if you strongly value minimalism over convenience. Beast is unusual enough that you will probably custom-draw most of the UI either way, but SDL gives you a sturdier floor while you do it. The one caveat is that SDL has its own evolving edges too; for example, there are still active discussions around renderer/thread behavior and some windowing quirks, while sokol’s Vulkan support is explicitly described as experimental.  ￼

So, shortest version:

SDL   = heavier, safer, faster to "app"
sokol = thinner, cleaner, faster to "engine"

For Beast right now, I think SDL is more likely to get you to "it works" in two weeks.







