You’re remembering correctly in spirit, but the exact detail is a bit more nuanced.

Factorio does use SDL, but not as its core engine. It uses SDL primarily as a platform layer.

⸻

what Factorio actually does

Factorio’s stack is roughly:

custom engine (rendering, simulation, ui)
+ SDL (window, input, platform glue)
+ OpenGL (rendering backend)

So SDL is used for:
	•	window creation
	•	input (mouse, keyboard)
	•	cross-platform abstraction

But not for UI widgets or high-level rendering.

⸻

why this matters for Beast

This is almost exactly the pattern you’re converging on:

thin platform layer
+ fully custom UI + rendering
+ explicit systems

Factorio didn’t rely on:
	•	OS UI toolkits
	•	heavy frameworks
	•	generic widget systems

They built:
	•	their own UI system
	•	their own layout
	•	their own rendering pipeline

Because their UI is:
	•	dense
	•	highly interactive
	•	simulation-driven

Sound familiar.

⸻

the key takeaway

Factorio didn’t choose SDL because it’s "easy UI."

They chose it because:

it disappears

It solves:
	•	platform headaches
	•	input differences
	•	windowing

And then gets out of the way.

⸻

why this is relevant to your sokol vs sdl decision

Your options now look like:

SDL approach (Factorio-style)

SDL = platform layer
you = everything else

sokol approach

sokol = even thinner platform + gfx layer
you = everything else

So the real difference is:

SDL   → slightly more help, slightly more weight
sokol → slightly less help, maximum control


⸻

where Factorio maps to Beast

Your system:
	•	gallery UI
	•	command-driven interaction
	•	real-time updates
	•	custom workflows
	•	heavy background systems

Factorio:
	•	inventory grids
	•	toolbars
	•	map rendering
	•	simulation
	•	custom interaction model

Both require:

UI that is not "standard app UI"


⸻

subtle but important insight

Factorio didn’t optimize for:

fastest time to first UI

They optimized for:

long-term control and consistency

That’s why they built their own UI system.

⸻

what you should take from this

